 You might still have some work to do afterwards to perfect the fit, but I should hope that you will have the necessary information to know what the problems are and how to fix them.

47
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:25,000
 Given that there are a lot of different figure shapes and different things need to be done in the block making process to account for things such as a longer crotch length or a larger stomach, drafting just one block will not cover all of these issues.

48
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:32,000
 So besides the traditional hourglass shape that is the standard figure, I'll be drafting three other figure shapes.

49
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:35,000
 One of them is for my measurements and my figure shape.

50
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:44,000
 I have a triangular type figure as in the bottom part of the letter A, that kind of triangle. There is a larger difference between my waist and hips that is standard.

51
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:51,000
 My upper thighs are small in proportion to my bottom, and I also have a large protruding bottom and a dropped bottom.

52
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:55,000
 The second figure I'll be drafting for is Jane.

53
00:04:55,000 --> 00:05:02,000
 Jane is actually very slim and has a smallish waist, but her hips are smaller in proportion to her waist than is standard.

54
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:07,000
 So her torso is square in shape rather than the ideal hourglass.

55
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:15,000
 She also has smaller upper thighs than standard in comparison to her hips. She has a flatish bottom, but she also has a dropped bottom.

56
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:22,000
 The third figure is Anne. The widest part of Anne's hips is her high hip. So she has an apple shape, she has a large stomach.

57
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:28,000
 Her thighs are still smaller than is usual for her hip size and she has a flat bottom.

58
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:33,000
 Let me just clarify what I mean by the standard figure as it relates to pants.

59
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:37,000
 The standard figure has about 10 inches difference between the waist and the hips.

60
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:42,000
 So you can see by these shapes how the standard figure differs from the three I'm drafting.

61
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:48,000
 However, I want you to keep in mind that these flat two-dimensional shapes are very limiting and describing figures.

62
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:56,000
 The standard figure is not just about measurements, it's about the proportion with those measurements, and that's not obvious from these two-dimensional shapes.

63
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:00,000
 Fit is not only about measurements, it's about the proportion within those measurements.

64
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:05,000
 So this means that you could have the same measurements as the standard figure, but not have the same shape.

65
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:10,000
 So when I talk about the standard figure, it is the figure that the fashion industry is making clothes for.

66
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:14,000
 It includes the measurements and proportions favored by the fashion industry.

67
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:22,000
 When you go clothes shopping, if you find it relatively easy to find ready to wear clothing that fits, then you probably have a fairly standard figure.

68
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:29,000
 You might not know what size you are, but if you try on one size and it doesn't fit, then you go up or down a size and you find a size that fits.

69
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:33,000
 If you have a non-standard figure, it doesn't work like that.

70
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:39,000
 An example of that is you might get a pair of pants that fits you in the hips perfectly, but it's just enormous in the waist.

71
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:43,000
 Obviously, you can't go down a size for the waist because it won't fit you in the hips.

72
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:52,000
 And maybe you can't even put a belt on because cinching the waist in makes it far too short in the crotch and it's painful.

73
00:06:52,000 --> 00:07:01,000
 So if you have a non-standard figure, you may differ to the standard figure in some measurements, in shape or in measurements and shape.

74
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:05,000
 Now, there are two terms that relate to the structure of the pants that I want to cover.

75
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:10,000
 The top part of the pant is called the foundation. That's from the waist down to the crotch.

76
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:14,000
 That's the torso part. Below the crotch is the leg line.

77
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:19,000
 When we're drafting the block, it's important to focus on the foundation first and get that fitting correctly.

78
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:25,000
 You might not like how wide the leg is on this block. You might not like the tapering of the leg, but that's taste, that's fashion.

79
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:29,000
 And you can focus on the shape of the leg when drafting your patterns.

80
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:36,000
 We're concerned in getting enough ease in the leg to sit down and move, but other than that, the shape of the leg is not the focus when drafting the block.

81
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:41,000
 We want to focus on getting the foundation correct fitting well first.

82
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:50,000
 I want to go through the standard measurements that are commonly used for drafting pants that most block making instructions use for drafting them.

83
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:54,000
 Then show you where the assumptions are that create problems and non-standard figures.

84
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:59,000
 I'll then go through the extra measurements that you will need to draft your pants to get a better fit.

85
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:06,000
 Basically, we will, with the help of the extra measurements, do the fitting steps that are generally done after you draft the block.

86
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:09,000
 For example, generally you draft the block, you make your twile.

87
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:15,000
 Then you go to the fitting section of a book that says, you know, if your twile doesn't fit these, the adjustments that you make

88
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:19,000
 and see how you make the adjustments for a large, bottom or large thighs or small thighs.

89
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:28,000
 Well, what we're going to do is we're going to try and get most of those main differences sorted out within the block making process before we make our first twile.

90
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:31,000
 First, we'll cover the common length measurements.

91
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:38,000
 Pant block making instructions will often use four or five length measurements, that is, vertical measurements down the length of your body.

92
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:41,000
 Firstly, is waist to low hip.

93
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:46,000
 Secondly, is the waist to the crotch level, which is also called the crotch depth.

94
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:49,000
 Waist to knee, which is the middle of the knee.

95
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:51,000
 And lastly, waist to ankle.

96
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:55,000
 You could alternatively do waist to floor, but we're going to do waist to ankle.

97
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:59,000
 So those were the length measurements, and now we come to the width measurements.

98
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:02,000
 Quite a few block making instructions only have two.

99
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:05,000
 These width measurements relate to the foundation of the block.

100
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:09,000
 Remember, the foundation is the torso part from the waist down to the crotch.

101
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:13,000
 As we covered earlier, the foundation is what we really want to focus on for fitting.

102
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:17,000
 Now, the first of the two width measurements is the hip measurement.

103
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:23,000
 So the circumference of the low hip, that is defined as the widest part of your body below the waist.

104
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:27,000
 The second of the width measurements is your waist circumference.

105
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:32,000
 Now, before we go any further, I want to talk a bit about the fact that this block is to the waist.

106
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:36,000
 Even if you hate waisted pants and all your pants are lower rise and down on your hips,

107
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:39,000
 you need to draft the block to your waist for various reasons.

108
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:44,000
 For one, if you want to draft your pants two inches down or one inch down from your waist,

109
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:47,000
 well, you need to know where your waist is to draft those pants.

110
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:49,000
 You need the waist as a reference point.

111
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:54,000
 Also, you may want to draft a jumpsuit, high waisted pants or other garments that need the waist.

112
00:09:54,000 --> 00:10:02,000
 So you definitely need to draft the pants to your waist, but then you can make your patterns at whatever depth suits you.

113
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:07,000
 Now, there are two other width measurements that are sometimes also used in block making instructions for pants.

114
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:14,000
 That's the high hip, which is generally around four to five inches down from the waist and the calf.

115
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:20,000
 We will use the high hip, but we won't be using the calf because I think we'll be adding sufficient ease to the knee

116
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:22,000
 so that it also fits you in the calf.

117
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:27,000
 If you have really large calf muscles, you'll have to take that into account when drafting your patterns.

118
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:33,000
 Now, we're going to look at some of the assumptions in the block making instructions that use just the width measurements

119
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:36,000
 that we've covered so far, the hip, high hip and waist.

120
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:40,000
 Those are not enough to draft a well-fitting block for some of us.

121
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:44,000
 The first assumption is the lengths of the crotch extensions.

122
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:47,000
 They are shown as the pink lines in this graphic.

123
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:53,000
 The green lines are the hip measurement and the pink portion is the crotch extension.

124
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:59,000
 The crotch extension is the bit of fabric that goes between your legs to create the bifurcated garment.

125
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:06,000
 In most block making instructions, these crotch extensions are calculated as a proportion of your hip.

126
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:16,000
 But if you really look at the pants, you should notice that the hip plus extension is really the measurement of your upper thigh,

127
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:18,000
 so your thigh at crotch level.

128
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:22,000
 So basically, the thigh measurement is being assumed.

129
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:26,000
 When I say it's assumed, for a standard figure, it simply works out.

130
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:33,000
 For that hip measurement, that calculation that they do for the crotch extension works out to be correct for their thigh.

131
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:39,000
 But for non-standard figures, that crotch extension will mean either that you have too much ease in the thigh

132
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:43,000
 or you have not enough length there in the thigh.

133
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:50,000
 So we will add the upper thigh measurement to the list of measurements that will help us get a better fit.

134
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:55,000
 So remember, I covered earlier how much ease is in the trouser, the slack and the jeans.

135
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:00,000
 The trouser was about four inches ease, the slack two and a half, jeans one to two inches ease.

136
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:07,000
 Well, to give you an example of how this makes a difference to me, if I calculate my back and frontage extensions on my hip,

137
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:15,000
 I end up with close to four inches ease in the thigh on a slack, which is apparently the amount of ease needed for trousers rather than slacks.

138
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:20,000
 And for trousers, I end up with five and three-quarter inches ease instead of four.

139
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:26,000
 So obviously it's best to start with our thigh measurement and add the amount of ease that we need for a slack,

140
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:33,000
 rather than use some kind of calculation based on our hip, which may or may not work out well for us.

141
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:41,000
 Now the second main assumption that is made in most block making instructions is related to that same extension.

142
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:50,000
 With a standard figure, the extension that's calculated based as a percentage of the hip not only gives the desired amount of ease in the thigh,

143
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:58,000
 it also just happens to magically end up with a correct crotch length for both the front and the back blocks.

144
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:03,000
 Unfortunately, it doesn't work out so neatly or magically for non-standard figures,

145
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:07,000
 and you'll end up with a crotch length that's too short or too long,

146
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:12,000
 or you might actually have the crotch length, but it's all in the thigh where you don't want it.

147
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:19,000
 So if we add the crotch length to our list of measurements and we make it exactly for our correct crotch length,

148
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:25,000
 and we put it in the correct place, not just add it to the crotch extension which makes it bigger in the thigh,

149
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:29,000
 then we will have a better fitting block at the end of it.

150
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:36,000
 Now just on that same topic, some block making instructions say that if you don't have the crotch length you need,

151
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:41,000
 then you extend the extension, but remember that that makes the thigh bigger.

152
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:49,000
 Earlier I mentioned that if I draft pants with instructions that base the extension on my hip measurement, I end up with too much ease in the thigh,

153
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:54,000
 much too much ease, and yet the crotch length is still too short.

154
00:13:54,000 --> 00:14:00,000
 So I've already got a lot of ease, and if I then extend it further to get my crotch length,

155
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:10,000
 then I have just an enormous amount of ease in my thigh, and then my pants end up looking like a very unflattering pair of jodppers.

156
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:18,000
 So now we'll go through the measurements we need in a bit of detail, particularly to talk about how to take them and some exceptions for different body shapes.

157
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:20,000
 Firstly, waist to ankle.

158
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:25,000
 Measure your waist to ankle down the side of your body, not the center front or the center back.

159
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:34,000
 Make sure that when you're taking your measurements, you tie a piece of elastic around your waist so that you are always measuring from the same spot for the vertical measurements.

160
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:39,000
 Secondly, waist to high hip and your high hip circumference.

161
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:42,000
 Measure down four to five inches from your waist.

162
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:46,000
 Again, at the side of your body, not the center front or the center back.

163
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:53,000
 When I say four to five inches, if you're quite sure, make that four, if you're a medium height, four and a half, if you're tall, make that five inches.

164
00:14:53,000 --> 00:15:01,000
 So you are noting down two measurements, the depth you are taking the measurement and the circumference at that depth.

165
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:05,000
 Now your waist to low hip measurement and your low hip circumference.

166
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:11,000
 Again, the vertical measurement is taken down the side of your body, not the center front or the center back.

167
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:17,000
 Generally, your low hip is the widest part of your torso below your waist and above the legs.

168
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:28,000
 You measure not only the circumference, but the depth from your waist to where you are taking that measurement so that you know where down your body you are the widest.

169
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:43,000
 Now there are a couple of exceptions. If the widest part of your body is at your high hip or if the widest part of your body is at your crotch level, I don't want you to use that depth or that measurement as your low hip measurement.

170
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:49,000
 Now I'll give you the reason so it makes sense. We want two measurements between your waist and your crotch level.

171
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:59,000
 So if your high hip or your crotch level is the widest part, then consider your low hip to be two and three quarter inches above your crotch level.

172
00:15:59,000 --> 00:16:08,000
 So take the measurement at two and three quarter inches above your crotch level and use that measurement as your low hip measurement.

173
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:15,000
 Do not use the widest part of your body for that low hip measurement.

174
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:22,000
 Okay, now I just want to clarify because for the high hip, it's obvious that you've got that high hip measurement there as part of your block.

175
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:28,000
 But if your widest at your crotch level you might think, well, my block is not going to be wide enough.

176
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:37,000
 If the widest part of your body is around your crotch level, then you will get your width through both your thigh measurement and the crotch curve.

177
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:42,000
 And it will make sense when you watch the videos where I'm drafting those blocks.

178
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:52,000
 So to reiterate, if the widest part of your body is at the crotch level or if it's at your high hip, for the purpose of drafting this block,

179
00:16:52,000 --> 00:17:02,000
 you will consider your low hip to be two and three quarter inches above your crotch level and you will measure there and you will use the measurement that is at that level.

180
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:06,000
 Now your crotch depth and upper thigh circumference.

181
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:14,000
 Tie a piece of elastic around your upper thigh right up at crotch level. Make sure the elastic is parallel to the floor when you look at it from the front and the side.

182
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:21,000
 Measure down from your waist, down side, not the front or the back, from your waist to the elastic.

183
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:28,000
 Again, you want to note the depth measurement, which is the crotch depth, and we want the circumference, the thigh circumference.

184
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:37,000
 Now your knee depth and knee circumference. Make sure you measure again down the side from the waist to the mid knee.

185
00:17:37,000 --> 00:17:43,000
 For the circumference, make sure your knee is fully bent so you can sit comfortably in the pants.

186
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:50,000
 Now we need the crotch length and we need it split between the front and the back, which is not just the full crotch length divided by two.

187
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:58,000
 For example, my crotch length is almost four and a half inches more than my front crotch length.

188
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:07,000
 Now the standard way to take this measurement is to get a tape measure and measure from your center front through your legs up to the center back or from the center back through your legs up to the center front from waist to waist.

189
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:14,000
 Getting this measurement correct is essential, but it's the kind of measurement that you can take five times and get five different results.

190
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:20,000
 And you're not really sure if which one is right. So I have a suggestion of how to get this measurement correct.

191
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:26,000
 It is a bit fiddly. It might sound odd. It's a bit time consuming, but it's a crucial measurement to get right.

192
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:34,000
 And if you really want a well-fitting pair of pants, you might save yourself grief if you take my suggestion.

193
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:37,000
 So in the next slide, I'll show you what I'm talking about.

194
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:49,000
 Now this is hard to explain and hard to show you because my real life one is no more clear than this graphic that I've created to try and show you what I'm talking about.

195
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:53,000
 So you just have to pay attention and listen. It's going to take a bit of time.

196
00:18:53,000 --> 00:18:57,000
 I'm showing you here what I suggest you make and wear for 10 minutes.

197
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:01,000
 You'll need to wear something like very close-fitting pair of light bike shorts.

198
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:08,000
 You're going to make this wear it over a pair of bike shorts around the house for a little while. Sit down in it, bend down in it and see if it's comfortable.

199
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:12,000
 See if it pulls down the back or not. You will be sure of the measurement at the end.

200
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:16,000
 So you need a firm piece of elastic to tie around your waist.

201
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:21,000
 Don't use really wide elastic. It will be hard to determine where your waistline is on the width of that elastic.

202
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:25,000
 Now in this graphic, the elastic is in the orange bit.

203
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:31,000
 So you'll then need a piece of twill tape or some kind of very stable tape with no stretch in it whatsoever.

204
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:35,000
 So that's shown by the black tape on this graphic.

205
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:40,000
 Now here are the instructions. Tie the elastic around your waist so that it's firm but not too tight.

206
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:43,000
 You'll need to get it over your hips so it needs to stretch that much.

207
00:19:43,000 --> 00:19:47,000
 But it needs to be firm elastic and it needs to fit comfortably around your waist.

208
00:19:47,000 --> 00:19:56,000
 Once you've tied it off, measure two halfway marks keeping the mark away from the tie and mark the halfway points with a texture, a permanent marker.

209
00:19:56,000 --> 00:20:00,000
 On one of those halfway points, fold over and sew down a piece of twill tape.

210
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:04,000
 Sew it onto the elastic so it doesn't move or over the elastic. Make sure that it's firm.

211
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:10,000
 So put this on over your hips onto your waist so that it's sewn in of the twill tape is at your centre back.

212
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:14,000
 And pull the other end of the twill tape through your legs and bring it up over the elastic.

213
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:21,000
 Kind of like using your tape except with your tape you're not going to wear it around and you're not going to want to sew your tape measure.

214
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:24,000
 So hold it there and pull it tight.

215
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:27,000
 Let it loose until it feels comfortable but not too loose.

216
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:31,000
 Mark the point at the front where it's fold over or put a safety pin in there and take it off.

217
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:39,000
 Once you've taken it off, sew the twill tape and cut off the rest of the tape, maybe keeping just a little bit in case you need to let it out again.

218
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:49,000
 On the sewing machine, sew down the second end. When it's sewn and it will look something like the graphic shown, put it on over your by shorts and wear it for 10 minutes.

219
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:52,000
 Sit down in it. See if it pulls down at the back.

220
00:20:52,000 --> 00:20:59,000
 If it pulls down a tiny fraction that's okay. If it pulls down a lot, you'll need to let it out a bit and re-sew it.

221
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:07,000
 If it's loose and tighten it, when you're absolutely sure that it's the right length, you'll need to reach between your legs and mark the point between the front and the back.

222
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:11,000
 Put a safety pin in there or mark it somehow.

223
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:20,000
 Use the seam in the bike shorts that would indicate where the front ends and the back starts because the bike short seam will sit in the correct place for your body generally.

224
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:26,000
 With that point clearly, Mark, take this off and measure the back length and the front length.

225
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:33,000
 You'll need to decide whether you need to measure from the top of the elastic or the bottom of the elastic, make sure you're consistent.

226
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:38,000
 And as I said, that elastic should not be very wide, so hopefully it shouldn't make too much difference.

227
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:43,000
 Now keep this tiny little sumo nappy or whatever you want to call it. Don't throw it away, seriously.

228
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:50,000
 So if you when you make your twile, it seems that the crotch length might be wrong and you're not sure that the front and back ratio is correct, try this on again.

229
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:56,000
 If only to confirm that you've got it right. If something is wrong in the twile, at least you can be sure of your crotch length.

230
00:21:56,000 --> 00:22:05,000
 Seriously, I've tried mine on a number of times when I started this and I still have it and it has been invaluable.

231
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:14,000
 So again, it's time consuming, it's a bit fiddly, but if you are at all unsure about your crotch length, I suggest you do this.

232
